body: "## Observed (2026-07-20, this repository)\n`pm config set ids_token_length 6` against a sparse tracked settings.json produced a 128-insertion diff: every implicit default materialized (locks.wait_ms, checkpoints, history.compact_policy, full extensions.policy block, telemetry block incl. endpoint, context sections, schema block, search rerank/query_expansion, vector_store.collection_name...), and the explicitly stored `validation.parent_reference: \"warn\"` (a VALID enum per settings-validator vLiteral(\"warn\",\"strict_error\")) was replaced with \"strict_error\" in the same write.\n\n## Why it matters\n1. Frozen defaults: materialized values no longer track future default changes (e.g. telemetry endpoint churn never reaches the workspace) — the file silently pins today's defaults.\n2. Multi-agent conflict surface: a fully materialized singleton file maximizes cross-branch overlap exactly where pm-xdn6's config merge driver has no per-key semantics; two branches each touching one unrelated key now conflict across the whole file.\n3. Intent loss: explicit stored values flattened to effective/normalized values (warn -> strict_error, likely via governance layering writing the effective value back) destroy the user's recorded choice even when runtime behavior was already equivalent.\n\n## Direction\nSparse persistence: write only keys that differ from defaults (or at minimum only the mutated key), keep normalization read-side, and add a round-trip regression spec."
